`crates/ctx-cage/assets/` holds static configuration files bind-mounted into
the sandboxed container at cage setup time — they are data, not code, and
their contracts are entirely about what gets mounted where and why the
specific values were chosen.

Two files govern network behavior inside the offline netns: `cage-nsswitch.conf`
(mounted at `/etc/nsswitch.conf`) enables `files`+`dns` resolution, while
`cage-resolv.conf` (mounted at `/etc/resolv.conf`) points DNS at an
intentionally unreachable TEST-NET-1 address so lookups fail slowly instead
of busy-looping the CPU. These two are coupled only through the cage's mount
setup code (not present in this directory) — an editor changing one should
check that the other still makes sense for the same offline-network model.
Neither has any other consumer.

`cage-rules.md` is unrelated to the network files — it's a prompt asset
injected into the agent's session, defining the operating contract (real
writable repo, native tools, ignore stale brokered-access docs). Wording
changes here affect agent behavior directly, not sandbox mechanics.

All three files are mounted read-only and consumed by the (external) cage
setup code; nothing in this directory itself enforces the mounts or reads
these files at runtime.